In [geology](/Geology), a rock—or stone, if you must use the vernacular—is fundamentally a naturally occurring solid mass. It's an aggregate, a collection, of [minerals](/Mineral) or [mineraloid](/Mineraloid) matter. Think of it as a composition, defined by its constituent minerals, its [chemical composition](/Chemical_compound), and, crucially, the story of its formation. These aren't just inert lumps; they are the very bones of our planet, forming the Earth's outer solid layer, the [crust](/Earth%27s_crust), and extending deep into its interior, save for the molten chaos of the [outer core](/Earth%27s_outer_core) and those pockets of [magma](/Magma) lurking in the [asthenosphere](/Asthenosphere). The study of these formations is a sprawling affair, touching on [petrology](/Petrology) and [mineralogy](/Mineralogy), among other geological subdisciplines. And while we often limit our gaze to Earth, the principles extend to [planetary geology](/Planetary_geology), allowing us to ponder the rocks of other celestial bodies. A rather grand obsession, wouldn't you say?

Rocks are typically corralled into three main camps: [igneous](/Igneous_rock), [sedimentary](/Sedimentary_rock), and [metamorphic](/Metamorphic_rock). The first, igneous, is born from the cooling of [magma](/Magma) within the crust, or the fiery descent of [lava](/Lava) onto the surface, or even the crushing depths of the seabed. Sedimentary rocks, on the other hand, are the result of [diagenesis](/Diagenesis) and [lithification](/Lithification) – fancy terms for the compaction and cementing of [sediments](/Sediment). These sediments, in turn, are the weathered, transported, and deposited remnants of older rocks, a testament to time's relentless work. Finally, metamorphic rocks are the survivors, the transformed, the ones that have endured immense pressures and temperatures, bending and reshaping without succumbing to complete melting.

Humans, predictably, have been drawn to rocks since the dawn of our existence. The [Stone Age](/Stone_Age) is a rather blunt testament to this, a period defined by the development of stone tools. Later, rock became the very foundation of our [infrastructure](/Infrastructure), the silent witness to our burgeoning civilizations. [Mining](/Mining), a rather desperate scramble for resources, allowed us to unearth rocks and the precious minerals they held, including, of course, [metals](/Metal). And in our ceaseless quest to manipulate the world, we've even managed to create our own rock-like substances, such as [concrete](/Concrete). A rather ambitious, if slightly crude, endeavor.

### Study

•
Further information: [Geology](/Geology), [Petrology](/Petrology), and [Mineralogy](/Mineralogy)

The study of Earth and its components, including these geological formations, is, rather obviously, [geology](/Geology). [Petrology](/Petrology) delves into the character and origin of rocks, while [mineralogy](/Mineralogy) focuses on the building blocks themselves. This pursuit of knowledge, this dissection of stone, has been instrumental in shaping our understanding of Earth's history, the evolution of human history through [archaeology](/Archaeological), and the very fabric of our [engineering](/Engineering) and [technology](/Technology).

While theories about rocks and their origins have been around since, well, forever, their formal scientific study solidified in the 19th century. The theory of [Plutonism](/Plutonism) emerged then, and the discovery of [radioactive decay](/Radioactive_decay) in 1896 was a game-changer, enabling the [radiometric dating](/Radiometric_dating) of rocks. The more recent understanding of [plate tectonics](/Plate_tectonics), developed in the latter half of the 20th century, has further illuminated the grand, slow dance of our planet.

### Classification

•
See also: [Formation of rocks](/Formation_of_rocks)

A [balancing rock](/Balancing_rock) called [Kummakivi](/Kummakivi) (literally "strange stone" ) &#91;3&#93;

Rocks, at their core, are composed of mineral grains – [crystalline solids](/Crystalline_solids) meticulously assembled from atoms [chemically bonded](/Chemical_bond) into an orderly structure. &#91;4&#93; Some, however, contain [mineraloids](/Mineraloid) – rigid, mineral-like substances, such as [volcanic glass](/Volcanic_glass), &#91;5&#93; that lack that inherent crystalline order. The precise mix and abundance of these minerals are dictated by the rock's genesis.

Most rocks are dominated by [silicate minerals](/Silicate_minerals), compounds defined by their silica tetrahedra within their [crystal lattice](/Crystal_lattice). These silicate minerals account for a staggering three-quarters of all known mineral species and about 95% of the [earth's crust](/Crust_(geology)). &#91;6&#93; The proportion of [silica](/Silica) within a rock or mineral is a primary determinant of its name and characteristics. &#91;7&#93;

Rock [outcrop](/Outcrop) along a mountain creek near [Orosí](/Oros%C3%AD), [Costa Rica](/Costa_Rica).

Beyond their mineralogical makeup, rocks are classified by their chemical composition, [permeability](/Permeability_(earth_sciences)), the [texture](/Texture_(geology)) of their constituent particles, and their [particle size](/Particle_size_(grain_size)). These physical traits are, in essence, the fingerprints of the processes that forged them. &#91;5&#93; And the [rock cycle](/Rock_cycle) is the grand narrative of transformation, describing how rocks evolve from one type to another over eons. This cycle gives rise to the three principal classes: [igneous](/Igneous_rock), [sedimentary](/Sedimentary_rock), and [metamorphic](/Metamorphic_rock).

Within these broad categories lie countless subdivisions. It's important to understand that the boundaries between rock types are not always stark. They often transition, blurring into one another as mineral proportions shift. Think of it as a gradient, a continuous spectrum where definitions are merely selected points along the way. &#91;8&#93;

#### Igneous rock

•
Main article: [Igneous rock](/Igneous_rock)

Sample of igneous [gabbro](/Gabbro)

The term "igneous" itself, derived from the [Latin](/Latin) word *igneus* meaning "of fire," hints at its fiery birth. &#91;9&#93; Igneous rock is forged through the cooling and [solidification](/Freezing) of [magma](/Magma) or [lava](/Lava). This molten material originates from partial melts of pre-existing rocks, either in the [planet](/Planet)'s [mantle](/Mantle_(geology)) or [crust](/Crust_(geology)). Such melting typically occurs due to one of three triggers: a rise in temperature, a drop in pressure, or a change in chemical composition. &#91;10&#93; &#58;&#8202;591–599&#8202;

Igneous rocks fall into two primary classifications:

• [Plutonic](/Plutonic), or [intrusive](/Intrusion), rocks are formed when magma cools and [crystallizes](/Crystallization) slowly beneath the Earth's surface, within the [Earth's crust](/Earth%27s_crust). [Granite](/Granite) is a classic example of this type.

• Volcanic, or [extrusive](/Extrusive_(geology)), rocks are the result of magma reaching the surface, erupting as lava or fragmented ejecta. These form rocks like [pumice](/Pumice) or [basalt](/Basalt). &#91;5&#93;

As magmas ascend towards the surface, they tend to become enriched in silica, a process known as [magma differentiation](/Magma_differentiation). This happens for two main reasons: minerals with lower silica content crystallize out of the magma as it cools (following [Bowen's reaction series](/Bowen%27s_reaction_series)), and the magma can assimilate surrounding crustal rock ([country rock](/Country_rock_(geology))), which is generally silica-rich. Consequently, silica content is the most critical chemical factor in classifying igneous rocks. &#91;7&#93; The concentration of [alkali metal oxides](/Alkali_metal_oxide) ranks second in importance. &#91;11&#93;

Igneous rocks constitute approximately 65% of the Earth's crust by volume. Of this significant portion, basalt and [gabbro](/Gabbro) make up 66%, granite accounts for 16%, and [granodiorite](/Granodiorite) and [diorite](/Diorite) represent 17%. Syenite and ultramafic rocks are comparatively rare, at 0.6% and 0.3% respectively. The [oceanic crust](/Oceanic_crust) is overwhelmingly basalt (99%), an igneous rock of [mafic](/Mafic) composition. Conversely, [granitoids](/Granitoids)—a group including granite—dominate the [continental crust](/Continental_crust). &#91;12&#93; &#91;13&#93;

#### Sedimentary rock

•
Main article: [Sedimentary rock](/Sedimentary_rock)

Sedimentary [sandstone](/Sandstone) with [iron oxide](/Iron_oxide) bands

Sedimentary rocks are formed at the Earth's surface through the accumulation and subsequent cementation of fragments derived from older rocks, minerals, or organic matter. &#91;14&#93; Alternatively, they can form as chemical precipitates or through organic growth in water, a process known as [sedimentation](/Sedimentation). This involves the settling and accumulation of particulate matter, whether it's rock fragments ([clastic](/Clastic) sediments) or organic debris ([detritus](/Detritus)), or the precipitation of minerals from a [solution](/Solution_(chemistry)) (forming [evaporites](/Evaporite)). These accumulated materials then undergo compaction and cementation under moderate temperatures and pressures, a process collectively termed [diagenesis](/Diagenesis). &#91;5&#93; &#58;&#8202;265–280&#8202; &#91;15&#93; &#58;&#8202;147–154&#8202;

Before deposition, sediments are initially formed by the [weathering](/Weathering) of existing rocks in a source area, driven by agents of [denudation](/Denudation) such as [water](/Water), [wind](/Wind), [ice](/Ice), [mass movement](/Mass_wasting), or [glaciers](/Glacier). These agents then transport the weathered material to its depositional site. &#91;5&#93; Sedimentary rocks constitute about 7.9% of the Earth's crust by volume. Of this, a striking 82% is composed of shales, with limestones making up 6%, and sandstones and [arkoses](/Arkose) accounting for the remaining 12%. &#91;13&#93; The presence of [fossils](/Fossil) is a common characteristic of sedimentary rocks, as they often preserve evidence of past life. Due to the influence of gravity, sedimentary rocks typically form in horizontal or near-horizontal layers, known as [strata](/Strata), and are sometimes referred to as stratified rocks. &#91;16&#93;

The [grain size](/Grain_size) of sediments and the particles within [clastic](/Clastic_rock) sedimentary rocks allows for further classification. The smallest particles are [clay](/Clay), followed by [silt](/Silt), then [sand](/Sand), and finally [gravel](/Gravel). Some classification systems also include [cobbles](/Cobble_(geology)) and [boulders](/Boulder) as measurements of size. &#91;17&#93;

#### Metamorphic rock

•
Main article: [Metamorphic rock](/Metamorphic_rock)

Metamorphic banded [gneiss](/Gneiss)

Metamorphic rocks are born from the transformation of any existing rock type – be it igneous, sedimentary, or even an older metamorphic rock – when subjected to conditions of [temperature](/Temperature) and [pressure](/Pressure) significantly different from those under which it originally formed. This process, known as [metamorphism](/Metamorphism), literally means "change in form." It results in profound alterations to the physical properties and chemical makeup of the rock. The original rock, the [protolith](/Protolith), transforms into new mineral types or different crystalline arrangements of existing minerals through [recrystallization](/Recrystallization_(geology)). &#91;5&#93; These transformative conditions are invariably more extreme than those found at the Earth's surface, typically exceeding temperatures of 150 to 200 °C and pressures of 1500 bars. &#91;18&#93; Such environments are commonly found, for instance, during the collision of [continental plates](/Continental_plates). &#91;19&#93; &#58;&#8202;31–33,&#8202;134–139&#8202; Metamorphic rocks represent a substantial 27.4% of the Earth's crust by volume. &#91;13&#93;

Metamorphic rocks are broadly categorized into three main classes based on their formation mechanism. [Contact metamorphism](/Contact_metamorphism) occurs when an intrusion of magma heats the surrounding rock, leading to a temperature-dominated transformation. [Burial metamorphism](/Burial_metamorphism), where sediments are buried deep within the Earth, is primarily pressure-driven, with temperature playing a lesser role. This process can yield rocks like [jade](/Jade). When both heat and pressure are significant factors, the process is termed [regional metamorphism](/Regional_metamorphism), typically associated with mountain-building events. &#91;7&#93;

Further classification divides metamorphic rocks into two general categories based on their structure: [foliated](/Foliation_(geology)) and non-foliated. Foliated rocks exhibit a layered or banded appearance, while non-foliated rocks do not. The specific name of the rock is then determined by its mineral content. [Schists](/Schist) are foliated rocks rich in [lamellar minerals](/Lamella_(materials)) like [micas](/Mica). [Gneisses](/Gneiss) are characterized by visible bands of varying lightness, with granite gneiss being a common example. Other foliated varieties include [slates](/Slate), [phyllites](/Phyllite), and [mylonites](/Mylonite). Among the well-known non-foliated metamorphic rocks are [marble](/Marble), [soapstone](/Soapstone), and [serpentine](/Serpentine_group). This group also includes [quartzite](/Quartzite)—a metamorphosed form of [sandstone](/Sandstone)—and [hornfels](/Hornfels). &#91;7&#93;

#### Extraterrestrial rocks

•
Main article: [Planetary geology](/Planetary_geology)

While our understanding of rocks is primarily Earth-centric, they are fundamental components of numerous celestial bodies across the universe. Within our own [Solar System](/Solar_System), planets like [Mars](/Mars), [Venus](/Venus), and [Mercury](/Mercury_(planet)) are rocky in composition, as are many of their [natural satellites](/Natural_satellite), [asteroids](/Asteroid), and [meteoroids](/Meteoroid). [Meteorites](/Meteorite) that reach Earth offer invaluable insights into extraterrestrial rocks and their composition, often proving to be denser than terrestrial rocks. Furthermore, space missions, such as the [Hayabusa](/Hayabusa) mission, have brought samples of asteroid rocks back to Earth for study. &#91;20&#93; Similarly, [Lunar rocks](/Moon_rock) and [Martian rocks](/Martian_rocks) have been subjected to rigorous scientific examination. &#91;21&#93;

### Human use

Ceremonial [cairn](/Cairn) of rocks, an [ovoo](/Ovoo), from [Mongolia](/Mongolia)

The interaction between humans and rocks has profoundly influenced the trajectory of cultural and technological development. For at least [2.5 million years](/Paleolithic), humans and their hominid ancestors have utilized rocks. &#91;22&#93; [Lithic technology](/Lithic_technology) represents one of the oldest and most enduring technological traditions. The extraction of metals from rocks through mining has been a pivotal driver of human progress, with its pace varying across regions depending on the availability of metallic resources.

#### Anthropic rock

•
Main article: [Anthropic rock](/Anthropic_rock)

[Anthropic rock](/Anthropic_rock) refers to synthetic or artificially restructured rock formations, a product of human activity. [Concrete](/Concrete), recognized as a human-made rock, is composed of natural and processed rock components and has a history dating back to [Ancient Rome](/Ancient_Rome). &#91;23&#93; Rocks can also be modified by incorporating other substances to create novel forms, such as [epoxy granite](/Epoxy_granite). &#91;24&#93; The development of [artificial stone](/Artificial_stone), like [Coade stone](/Coade_stone), further exemplifies this human endeavor. &#91;25&#93; Geologist James R. Underwood has even proposed classifying anthropic rock as a fourth fundamental category, alongside igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic rocks. &#91;26&#93;

#### Building

•
See also: [Building material § Stone or rock](/Building_material)

A stonehouse on the hill in [Sastamala](/Sastamala), Finland
[Raised garden bed](/Raised-bed_gardening) with natural stones

The strength of rock varies dramatically. Some [quartzites](/Quartzites) exhibit a [tensile strength](/Tensile_strength) exceeding 300 [MPa](/MPa), &#91;27&#93; while certain sedimentary rocks are so soft they can be crumbled by hand – they are described as [friable](/Friable). &#91;28&#93; For context, [structural steel](/Structural_steel) has a tensile strength of approximately 350 MPa. &#91;29&#93; As early as 4000 BCE, relatively soft, easily workable sedimentary rocks were quarried for construction in Egypt, &#91;30&#93; and stone was used for fortifications in [Inner Mongolia](/Inner_Mongolia) by 2800 BCE. &#91;31&#93; In Italy, the Romans extensively utilized the soft rock [tuff](/Tuff) for numerous buildings and bridges. &#91;32&#93; [Limestone](/Limestone) was a prevalent building material throughout the European Middle Ages &#91;33&#93; and remained so well into the 20th century. &#91;34&#93;

#### Mining

•
Main article: [Mining](/Mining)

[Mi Vida uranium mine](/Charles_Steen) near [Moab, Utah](/Moab,_Utah)

[Mining](/Mining) is the process of extracting valuable [minerals](/Mineral) or other [geological](/Geology) materials from the Earth. This can involve ore bodies, veins, or seams, and the term also encompasses the removal of soil. Recovered materials include [base metals](/Base_metals), [precious metals](/Precious_metals), [iron](/Iron), [uranium](/Uranium), [coal](/Coal), [diamonds](/Diamond), [limestone](/Limestone), [oil shale](/Oil_shale), [rock salt](/Sodium_chloride), [potash](/Potash), [construction aggregate](/Construction_aggregate), and [dimension stone](/Dimension_stone). Mining is essential for obtaining any material that cannot be cultivated through [agricultural](/Agriculture) processes or synthesized [artificially](/Chemical_synthesis) in a [laboratory](/Laboratory) or [factory](/Factory). In a broader sense, mining can refer to the extraction of any [resource](/Resource)—including [petroleum](/Petroleum), [natural gas](/Natural_gas), [salt](/Salt), or even [water](/Water)—from the Earth. &#91;36&#93;

The practice of mining rock and metals dates back to [prehistoric](/Prehistory) times. Modern mining operations involve systematic [prospecting](/Prospecting) for mineral deposits, assessing the economic viability of a proposed mine, extracting the target materials, and ultimately, reclaiming the land for subsequent use after operations cease. &#91;37&#93;

However, mining activities can inflict significant negative environmental impacts, both during operations and long after they have concluded. Recognizing these potential consequences, most nations have implemented regulations to mitigate the adverse effects of mining. &#91;38&#93;

#### Tools

•
Main article: [Stone tool](/Stone_tool)

Stone tools have been a constant companion to humans and earlier [hominids](/Hominidae) for millennia, with their use spanning millions of years. The [Stone Age](/Stone_Age) is, by definition, a period defined by the widespread application of stone tools. &#91;39&#93; Tools from the [Early Stone Age](/Early_Stone_Age) were rudimentary, consisting of simple implements like [hammerstones](/Hammerstone) and sharp flakes. The [Middle Stone Age](/Middle_Stone_Age) saw the development of tools with sharpened points, suitable for use as [projectile points](/Projectile_point), awls, or [scrapers](/Scraper_(archaeology)). By the [Late Stone Age](/Late_Stone_Age), tool development reflected increasing [craftsmanship](/Craftsmanship) and discernible cultural identities. &#91;40&#93; The advent of [metallurgy](/Metallurgy) eventually led to the widespread adoption of copper and bronze tools, largely superseding stone implements.

